\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces The Constraint Cascade Architecture. Four layers: Environment (L1), Interface (L2), Algorithm \& Weights (L3), Strategic Authority (L4). The epistemic gap (red dotted line) between L2 and L3 marks the boundary proven by \textit  {Dual Certificates}: output-only observation cannot recover internal state. Human labor operates at friction seams (amber lines): low-status labor (moderators, annotators) at the L2/L3 seam; high-status labor (alignment researchers) at the L3/L4 seam. Three cross-layer failure patterns: Override (red arc, above), Contamination (red arc, below), Compression. Scope of institutional response spans L2--L4.}}{3}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:cascade}{{1}{3}{The Constraint Cascade Architecture. Four layers: Environment (L1), Interface (L2), Algorithm \& Weights (L3), Strategic Authority (L4). The epistemic gap (red dotted line) between L2 and L3 marks the boundary proven by \textit {Dual Certificates}: output-only observation cannot recover internal state. Human labor operates at friction seams (amber lines): low-status labor (moderators, annotators) at the L2/L3 seam; high-status labor (alignment researchers) at the L3/L4 seam. Three cross-layer failure patterns: Override (red arc, above), Contamination (red arc, below), Compression. Scope of institutional response spans L2--L4}{figure.1}{}}
